## v1.4.0 — 2026-04-20 (evening)

- Changed by: ArchIdeas corpus fresh re-audit + 3-wave fixer + 3-pass scrub, 2026-04-20 evening
- Verification: verified-local

### What changed

- Added four new Failed Attempts rows:
  - Bibliography-entry change-note stubs (`ADDED — missing from original`, `Added during merge`, `Critical addition`) survive a clean literal-phrase scrub gate; extend R6 pattern list with bibliography suffixes.
  - Semantic-judgment phrases (`understated in the original`, `material gap in the original`, `[Original doc: — WRONG]`) are change-notes phrased as editorial commentary; need a separate semantic-pass scrub distinct from the literal-phrase pass.
  - Wave A fixer agents with `isolation: "worktree"` land on `main` anyway for some agent variants (2 of 3 this session); always run the `git merge-base --is-ancestor "$AGENT_COMMIT" main` check before Wave C narrow-patch and skip the patch step for on-main agents.
  - "Clean under current gate" ≠ "clean under all gates" — schedule at least two post-merge audit passes with intentionally-expanded pattern lists; Wave B clean is a local optimum.
- Added new Results & Parameters subsection "Expanded R6 pattern list (bibliography + semantic variants)" with three numbered grep passes.
- Added new Wave-A landing verification subsection showing the mandatory `merge-base --is-ancestor` loop.
- Appended new "Verified On" row for 2026-04-20 evening session.
- Bumped `version` 1.3.0 → 1.4.0; `date` stays 2026-04-20 (same day).

### Why

The 2026-04-20 evening session ran a full re-audit + 3-wave fixer + 3-pass scrub on the same ArchIdeas corpus that the morning v1.3.0 release was validated against. Two new hazard classes surfaced that the morning session did not hit: (1) bibliography entries carry their own sub-class of change-note suffixes that the literal-phrase R6 pattern list did not cover, and (2) two of three Wave A fixer agents landed commits on `main` directly despite explicit `isolation: "worktree"` config and prompt discipline. Both are generic hazards for the pattern, not session-specific. The skill update codifies three explicit grep passes and a mandatory per-agent landing check that the next invocation of this pattern must use from the start.

